<doc id="145126" wikidata="Q44382" url="?curid=145126" title="Principal ideal">
<text>In mathematics, specifically ring theory, a principal ideal is an ideal formula_1 in a ring formula_2 that is generated by a single element formula_3 of formula_2 through multiplication by every element of formula_5 The term also has another, similar meaning in order theory, where it refers to an (order) ideal in a poset formula_6 generated by a single element formula_7 which is to say the set of all elements less than or equal to formula_8 in formula_9

The remainder of this article addresses the ring-theoretic concept.

==Definitions==
* A &quot;left principal ideal&quot; of formula_2 is a subset of formula_2 given by formula_12 for some element formula_13
* A &quot;right principal ideal&quot; of formula_2 is a subset of formula_2 given by formula_16 for some element formula_13
* A &quot;two-sided principal ideal&quot; of formula_2 is a subset of formula_2 given by formula_20 for some element formula_21 namely, the set of all finite sums of elements of the form formula_22

While the definition for two-sided principal ideal may seem more complicated than for the one-sided principal ideals, it is necessary to ensure that the ideal remains closed under addition.

If formula_2 is a commutative ring, then the above three notions are all the same. In that case, it is common to write the ideal generated by formula_3 as formula_25 or formula_26

==Examples and non-examples==
* The principal ideals in the (commutative) ring formula_27 are formula_28 In fact, every ideal of formula_27 is principal (see ).
* In any ring formula_2, the sets formula_31 and formula_32 are principal ideals.
* For any ring formula_2 and element formula_21 the ideals formula_35 and formula_36 are respectively left, right, and two-sided principal ideals, by definition. For example, formula_37 is a principal ideal of formula_38
* In the commutative ring formula_39 of complex polynomials in two variables, the set of polynomials that vanish everywhere on the set of points formula_40 is a principal ideal because it can be written as formula_41 (the set of polynomials divisible by formula_8).
* In the same ring formula_39, the ideal formula_44 generated by both formula_8 and formula_46 is &quot;not&quot; principal. (The ideal formula_44 is the set of all polynomials with zero for the constant term.) To see this, suppose there was a generator formula_48 for formula_49 so formula_50 Then formula_51 contains both formula_8 and formula_53 so formula_48 must divide both formula_8 and formula_56 Then formula_48 must be a nonzero constant polynomial. This is a contradiction since formula_58 but the only constant polynomial in formula_59 is the zero polynomial.
* In the ring formula_60 the numbers where formula_61 is even form a non-principal ideal. This ideal forms a regular hexagonal lattice in the complex plane. Consider formula_62 and formula_63 These numbers are elements of this ideal with the same norm (two), but because the only units in the ring are formula_64 and formula_65 they are not associates.

==Related definitions==
A ring in which every ideal is principal is called &quot;principal&quot;, or a &quot;principal ideal ring&quot;. A &quot;principal ideal domain&quot; (PID) is an integral domain in which every ideal is principal. Any PID is a unique factorization domain; the normal proof of unique factorization in the integers (the so-called fundamental theorem of arithmetic) holds in any PID.

As an example, formula_27 is a principal ideal domain, which can be shown as follows. Suppose formula_67 where formula_68 and consider the surjective homomorphisms formula_69 Since formula_70 is finite, for sufficiently large formula_71 we have formula_72 Thus formula_73 which implies formula_1 is always finitely generated. Since the ideal formula_75 generated by any integers formula_3 and formula_77 is exactly formula_78 by induction on the number of generators it follows that formula_1 is principal.

==Properties==
Any Euclidean domain is a PID; the algorithm used to calculate greatest common divisors may be used to find a generator of any ideal.
More generally, any two principal ideals in a commutative ring have a greatest common divisor in the sense of ideal multiplication.
In principal ideal domains, this allows us to calculate greatest common divisors of elements of the ring, up to multiplication by a unit; we define formula_80 to be any generator of the ideal formula_81

For a Dedekind domain formula_82 we may also ask, given a non-principal ideal formula_1 of formula_82 whether there is some extension formula_85 of formula_2 such that the ideal of formula_85 generated by formula_1 is principal (said more loosely, formula_1 &quot;becomes principal&quot; in formula_85).
This question arose in connection with the study of rings of algebraic integers (which are examples of Dedekind domains) in number theory, and led to the development of class field theory by Teiji Takagi, Emil Artin, David Hilbert, and many others.

The principal ideal theorem of class field theory states that every integer ring formula_2 (i.e. the ring of integers of some number field) is contained in a larger integer ring formula_85 which has the property that &quot;every&quot; ideal of formula_2 becomes a principal ideal of formula_94 In this theorem we may take formula_85 to be the ring of integers of the Hilbert class field of formula_2; that is, the maximal unramified abelian extension (that is, Galois extension whose Galois group is abelian) of the fraction field of formula_82 and this is uniquely determined by formula_5

Krull&#x27;s principal ideal theorem states that if formula_2 is a Noetherian ring and formula_1 is a principal, proper ideal of formula_82 then formula_1 has height at most one.

